# TypeScript/Electron Prototype

This is the active prototype. It uses Electron for the desktop shell, React DOM for the renderer, Vite for bundling, and the TypeScript compiler for typechecking.

## Setup

```sh
npm install
```

This prototype uses npm and `package-lock.json`. Do not regenerate `yarn.lock`.

## Commands

```sh
npm start
```

Builds the renderer, Electron main process, and preload script, then launches Electron.

```sh
npm run typecheck
```

Runs `tsc --noEmit`.

```sh
npm run build
```

Builds without launching Electron.

```sh
npm run gen
```

Builds and runs the graph wrapper generator. This rewrites `src/graph/graph.ts` and `src/graph/renderIfs.ts`; inspect the diff after running it.

## Editing `.progred` Libraries

For mechanical graph edits, prefer a short throwaway TypeScript script over hand-editing the serialized JSON. A convenient pattern is to add a temporary Vitest file near the target library, load the `.progred` with `load`, mutate it through the generated graph API inside `withEnvironment`, write it back with `save`, run that one test file once, then delete the temporary file.

Use `process.cwd()` to locate files when running under Vitest; `import.meta.url` may not be a normal `file:` URL there.

## Code Style

This prototype intentionally leans toward expression-oriented, inlined TypeScript. Preserve existing inlining when editing code, and prefer inlining one-off intermediate values in new code unless a name represents a real concept, is reused, helps type inference, or makes a genuinely complex expression easier to read.
